\begin_layout Subsection*

\lang english
6.
 Policy Statement
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.1 Purpose and Governing Principle
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
The Department shall maintain a documented,
 tested,
 and IT Director-approved Continuity Plan that enables the restoration of IT services following any disruption affecting systems within the scope of this policy.
 Recovery planning under this policy governs failure scenarios;
 Service Level Agreement targets for normal operations are governed by 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:3.01"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
.
 The two frameworks are complementary and distinct —
 neither supersedes the other.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.2 Business Impact Analysis
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
The Business Impact Analysis (BIA) is a formal planning artifact owned by the Assistant IT Director and approved by the IT Director.
 The BIA is distinct from the Risk Register governed by 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:1.09"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
.
 The Risk Register produces risk scores;
 the BIA produces recovery planning outputs.
 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:1.09"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
's Criticality Analysis informs BIA inputs;
 the BIA produces the criticality classifications,
 RTOs,
 RPOs,
 backup minimums,
 and recovery sequence priority order that continuity execution depends upon.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
The BIA shall document,
 at minimum:
 a criticality classification assignment for each in-scope system and service using the four-class taxonomy defined in Section 6.4;
 the approved RTO for each criticality classification;
 the approved RPO for each criticality classification;
 the minimum backup frequency,
 retention period,
 and offsite storage requirement for each criticality classification;
 and the recovery sequence priority order across all in-scope systems.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
The BIA shall be reviewed and updated no less than annually and following any Significant or Emergency change as defined in 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:3.09"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
 that materially alters the service catalog or infrastructure.
 The IT Director shall approve each updated version before it takes effect.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.3 Continuity Plan
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
The Continuity Plan is a governed document maintained in Redmine by the Assistant IT Director.
 The Continuity Plan shall be protected from unauthorized disclosure and modification.
 The Continuity Plan shall contain,
 at minimum:
\end_layout

