\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
Continuity plan activation may occur through either of two pathways.
 Both pathways require the activation decision to be documented in the incident work order at the time it is made.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
\lang english
Objective Trigger
\series default
:
 When the projected or elapsed restoration time for a disrupted system exceeds the RTO established for that system's criticality classification in the BIA,
 the Incident Commander shall declare continuity plan activation and initiate recovery procedures under this policy.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
\lang english
Incident Commander Judgment Pathway
\series default
:
 The Incident Commander may declare continuity plan activation at any time,
 independent of whether the objective RTO threshold has been crossed,
 based on a documented professional assessment of operational conditions —
 for example,
 where the nature of the failure,
 resource availability,
 or cascading impact makes continued repair inadvisable before the RTO is breached.
 Qualitative assessments without supporting observations do not satisfy this requirement.
 The basis for the judgment shall be documented in the incident work order at the time of activation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.4 Asset Criticality Classification
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
The Department operates four asset classification classes for continuity and backup governance purposes.
 Specific RTO,
 RPO,
 and backup minimums for each classification are established in the BIA and approved by the IT Director.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Tier 1 —
 Mission Critical
\series default
:
 Systems whose failure immediately impairs the Department's ability to deliver mandated services or maintain operations across the County.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Tier 2 —
 Operationally Important
\series default
:
 Systems that support individual department functions.
 Their failure degrades service for specific departments but does not immediately impair County-wide operations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Tier 3 —
 Administrative / Deferrable
\series default
:
 Systems that provide operational convenience or supplementary capability.
 County operations continue normally without these systems.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Security Infrastructure
\series default
:
 Systems that support the Department's security monitoring,
 logging,
 and vulnerability management functions.
 Recovery priority is driven by security posture rather than operational impact;
 sequencing follows the three-state rule below.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
Recovery sequencing for Security Infrastructure is determined by the Incident Commander's declared event classification,
 documented in the incident work order:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Known non-security disruption:

\series default
 Hardware failure,
 utility outage,
 natural disaster,
 or other event with no security nexus,
 as declared by the Incident Commander.
 Security Infrastructure recovers at Tier 2 priority,
 in the second wave alongside Tier 2 operational systems.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Known or suspected security event
\series default
:
 Operational Handback received from Chapter 4,
 or security nexus not yet ruled out.
 Security Infrastructure recovers concurrently with Tier 1.
 Log visibility shall be confirmed before broader restoration proceeds,
 to ensure no residual threat is present before systems are returned to the environment.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Unknown or unclassified disruption
\series default
:
 Treated as a suspected security event until the Incident Commander explicitly declares otherwise.
 Security Infrastructure recovers concurrently with Tier 1 by default.
 This principle is consistent with 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:3.06"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
,
 under which uncertainty is resolved in favor of caution.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.5 Testing
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
The Assistant IT Director shall coordinate an annual tabletop exercise covering the full Continuity Plan.
 The exercise shall produce a written record documenting participants,
 scenarios tested,
 and findings,
 which the IT Director shall receive.
 IT staff designated for contingency roles shall receive contingency training within thirty days of assuming those responsibilities and following any significant change to the Continuity Plan or in-scope systems.
 Annual participation in the tabletop exercise satisfies the recurring training obligation;
 no additional training artifact is required.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
The Systems Administrator shall conduct quarterly backup restoration verification by restoring from backup to a non-production environment and confirming data integrity.
 Results shall be documented in a restoration verification record.
 Backup failures or integrity verification failures shall be escalated to the Assistant IT Director within one business day of identification.
 Specific test procedures are maintained in the Knowledge Base under 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:3.13"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
The most recent annual tabletop exercise record and the four most recent quarterly backup restoration verification records shall be retained with the Continuity Plan.
 Exceptions to the testing cadence require written IT Director approval and shall be documented in the Continuity Plan.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.6 Backup Governance
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
All in-scope systems shall have backups maintained in accordance with the parameters established in this section.
 The BIA shall define minimum backup frequency,
 retention period,
 and offsite storage requirements by asset classification,
 subject to IT Director approval.
 Operational procedures to execute,
 verify,
 and store backups in compliance with the BIA-approved parameters shall be maintained in the Knowledge Base under 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:3.13"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
.
 All backups shall be encrypted at rest and in transit regardless of the classification of the system being backed up.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.7 Operational Handback
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
Operational Handback is the mechanism by which operational recovery authority passes from Chapter 4 back to this policy following a cybersecurity incident.
 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:4.05"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
 governs Operational Handback initiation —
 the conditions under which the Incident Commander declares the Chapter 4 security response phase complete,
 the declaration procedure,
 and the documentation requirements on the Chapter 4 side.
 This policy governs the receiving obligations that attach upon Operational Handback.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
Chapter 4 authority holds until the Incident Commander explicitly declares Operational Handback.
 Ambiguity or assumption of handback is not permitted.
 Upon Operational Handback,
 the BIA-driven recovery priority order established in this policy governs operational restoration sequencing,
 subject to the Security Infrastructure sequencing rules in Section 6.4.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
For hybrid events where a cybersecurity incident has also caused infrastructure failure,
 Chapter 4 holds full authority through the security response phase.
 This policy receives authority for operational restoration only after explicit Operational Handback is declared.
 The Incident Commander's declaration shall be documented in the incident work order at the time it is made.
 Upon receiving Operational Handback,
 the Assistant IT Director shall confirm that the Continuity Plan's Operational Handback Protocol section has been consulted and that recovery sequencing is proceeding in accordance with the BIA priority order.
\end_layout

